How routing should think

Do not model routes too literally, like a fragile internet router table.
For Beast Comms, routing is probabilistic and social.

A node should ask:
	•	Is recipient directly reachable now?
	•	If not, which trusted node is most likely to encounter them or their locality?
	•	Which nearby node has best history delivering to that cluster?
	•	Is this worth replicating to 1 node or 3?
	•	Is this emergency traffic?
	•	Is battery or storage scarce?

So route knowledge is more like:
	•	"this courier often reaches village X by evening"
than
	•	"destination IP should go to next hop Y forever."

That is a better fit for intermittent networks.

⸻

Security model

This matters a lot.

Private messages
	•	end-to-end encrypted
	•	relays store ciphertext only
	•	metadata minimized where possible
	•	recipient set may still leak some routing information, so use recipient-group envelopes carefully

Public artifacts
	•	signed
	•	hash-addressed
	•	openly mirrored if user chooses

Trust scopes

Not every node should carry everything.

Users should be able to choose:
	•	family-only forwarding
	•	trusted-community forwarding
	•	public network participation
	•	emergency-only carrying for strangers

That keeps the system socially survivable.

⸻

What can fail without collapse

A good Beast comms design should survive loss of:
	•	one hub
	•	all hubs in a locality
	•	direct internet
	•	DNS
	•	one ISP
	•	SIM service on one carrier
	•	temporary total partition between regions
	•	many devices going offline
	•	duplicate or delayed packets
	•	partially corrupted local caches

If a message exists on several trusted nodes and is content-addressed with signed custody logs, the network can heal.

⸻

Design caution

There are two big traps.

Trap 1: making the routing state too global

A smartphone should not try to know the whole world.
It should know:
	•	itself
	•	its people
	•	its localities
	•	a compressed summary of adjacent route opportunities
	•	a few trusted bridges / hubs
	•	optional DHT shard responsibility if participating deeply

Think federated postal districts, not "global routing table on every phone."

Trap 2: rewarding spam instead of service

If rewards are too naive, people will bounce junk around to farm Wings.

So only reward:
	•	useful delivery
	•	successful custody across meaningful boundaries
	•	participation validated by recipient-side or destination-side evidence
	•	long-duration storage when truly needed
	•	bridge value during real partitions

